That quote couldn‚Äôt ring truer.

So much of what we ruminate and dwell on does have a certain degree of control over us if we aren‚Äôt discerning about the tenants of real estate in our mind.

Recently I was chatting with my brother and was rehashing some of my current angst. We‚Äôre pretty close, so I have the same but different versions of phone-calls with him fairly often. 

This is not fun to admit, but he is a trained mental health professional, and can be really wise sometimes. ü§ì

He‚Äôs great and listened to my thoughts, but then he noted that I give a lot of head space to things and people way outside of my control. And these thoughts become cyclical. (Then he had to hang up to get boba tea or something else more important üòÇ) 

He was spot on. And I‚Äôve since been wondering #1. why I allow that? And #2. Where is that taking me? 

Did you know: ‚Äúthe average person has about 12,000 to 60,000 thoughts per day. Of those thousands of thoughts, 80% were negative, and 95% were exactly the same repetitive thoughts as the day before.‚Äù (NSF)

So, if my repetitive thoughts aren‚Äôt healthy and remain uninterrupted, they will just become my entire narrative or perception of reality. 

I want to steward the sacred space of my mind well, and giving certain brain trains that kind of power and influence isn‚Äôt always what is best or healthy. 

Since that chat, I‚Äôve been practicing a simple pause. I‚Äôm still in progress for sure, but I‚Äôm just more aware of my mental real estate, a space that I think is now less accommodating to toxic, or just simply unhelpful, ruminations. 

I love that God himself equips us for this kind of stewardship: 

2 Timothy 1:7: ‚ÄúFor God did not give us a spirit of timidity or cowardice or fear, but He has given us a spirit of power and of love and of sound judgment and personal discipline [abilities that result in a calm, well-balanced mind and self-control].‚Äù
